Project 3 - Optimal Selection

This project is an assignment for CS2430 - Discrete Structures. It features an altered knapsack problem with three greedy algorithms,
a brute force algorithm, and a dynamic programming algorithm. The problem includes a list of twelve experiments with two variables:
weight and rating. The objective is to maximize the rating and minimize the weight, given that only 700 kg are allowed in the subset.
The greedy methods solve the problem directly by selecting a single variable, with which they filter the list of experiments. The
brute force method computes every possible combination of experiments and returns the optimal subset. The dynamic programming
method constructs a large two-dimensional integer array filled with ratings in ascending order from left to right and top to bottom,
remember past calculations and building the optimal subset as the table fills. The dynamic programming method has a better time
complexity than the brute force method, although it takes up more space to function. These two approaches are guaranteed to return
the optimal subset but take much longer to do so than the greedy methods. The results from each of these methods are displayed in the
console and compared to each other for analysis. The best combinations of experiments are shown, along with those generated with the
greedy methods.
